When Nelson Mandela became South Africa’s first democratically elected president in 1994, there were good reasons to think the country's neighbors would follow suit, most notably Burundi: Both had fought long-running guerrilla wars and experienced plunges in violence after one of those wars ended.

(From Frontline's A Bad War: Lost in Afghanistan).

The new face of insurgent “leader” in Afghanistan has many mothers to tout. Sami-ul-Haq, population 528, lives in a village near Pakistan’s treacherous border with Afghanistan. Known as the “father of the Taliban,” he has been waging war against U.S. and international forces from Pakistan’s remote tribal areas. He also helped recruit thousands of religious zealots with radical interpretations of Islam for Taliban brigades not only in Afghanistan, but now in far-flung Yemen.

In addition, Haq began training jihadist fighters in northwestern Afghanistan across the border in Pakistan in 1984, where they were mentored by Abdullah Azzam, a leader of the jihadist Arab volunteers to fight Soviet aggression. The training sessions were held in one of Haq’s madrassas, the Faiz-ul Uloom school for boys.
